bergmark_d wrote:

&gt;
&gt; So I&#39;ve used Heritrix to download a Web page, and I have
&gt; the page content as a CharSequence (i.e., ReplayCharSequence).
&gt; The CharSequence interface in Java says that its toString()
&gt; method should be a string with the characters in the same
&gt; order as in the CharSequence.
&gt;
&gt; I do not think that ReplayCharSequence.toString() is
&gt; correctly implemented.  (But I could be wrong.)
&gt;
&gt; Assume &quot;ReplayCharSequence cs&quot; has been defined.  Then
&gt; printing out &quot;cs.toString()&quot; gives me (the unexpected)
&gt; string,
&gt; &quot;org.archive.io.ReplayCharSequenceFactory$ByteReplayCharSequence...&quot;
&gt;
&gt; This is not the characters in &quot;cs&quot; but rather a string
&gt; representing &quot;cs&quot;, I guess.  Instead, if I print out
&gt; &quot;(cs.subSequence(0,cs.length()-1)).toString()&quot; I get the
&gt; expected output, namely the characters in &quot;cs&quot;.  This is
&gt; only because the &quot;subSequence&quot; method returns a
&gt; &quot;java.lang.CharSequence&quot;, where toString() is correctly
&gt; implemented.
&gt;
&gt; Here is the code I used:
&gt; System.out.println(&quot;First 100 bytes of page:&#92;n&quot;
&gt;                 + cs.subSequence(0,99));    // GOOD!
&gt; String s = cs.toString();
&gt; System.out.println(&quot;String version:&#92;n&quot; + s);   // BAD!
&gt; s = (cs.subSequence(0,cs.length()-1)).toString(); 
&gt; System.out.println(&quot;Second string version:&#92;n&quot; + s); // GOOD!
&gt;
&gt; D.
